{"title_page": "A. Y. Jackson", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name = A. Y. Jackson \n| image = Alexander Young Jackson.jpg\n| caption = Jackson at work in [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]] in Toronto.\n| birth_name = Alexander Young Jackson \n| birth_date = {{birth date|mf=yes|1882|10|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada\n| death_date = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1974|4|5|1882|10|3}}\n| death_place = [[Kleinburg]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| field = [[Painting]]\n| training = [[Monument-National]], [[Art Institute of Chicago]], [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] \n| movement = [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]]\n| works        =\n| patrons =\n| awards =\n}}\n\n'''Alexander Young Jackson''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CC|CMG}} (October 3, 1882 \u2013 April 5, 1974) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] painter and a founding member of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]]. Jackson made a significant contribution to the development of art in Canada, and was successful in bringing together the artists of [[Montreal]] and [[Toronto]].<ref name = NGC>{{cite web|author=A.Y. Jackson |url=http://www.gallery.ca/en/see/collections/artist.php?iartistid=2672 |title=A.Y. Jackson - National Gallery of Canada &#124; National Gallery of Canada |publisher=Gallery.ca |date= |accessdate=2014-07-26}}</ref> He exhibited with the Group of Seven from 1920. In addition to his work with the Group of Seven, his long career included serving as a war artist during World War I (1917\u201319) and teaching at the [[Banff School of Fine Arts]], from 1943 to 1949. In his later years he was [[artist-in-residence]] at the [[McMichael Gallery]] in [[Kleinburg, Ontario]].<ref name = NGC/><ref>[https://www.utoronto.ca/gallery/collection_pages/jackson.htm ] {{webarchive. |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051120043109/http://www.utoronto.ca/gallery/collection_pages/jackson.htm |date=November 20, 2005 }}</ref>\n\n== Early life and training ==\nAs a young boy, Jackson worked as an office boy for a [[lithograph]] company, after his father abandoned his family of six children. It was at this company that Jackson began his art training. In the evenings, he took classes at Montreal's [[Monument-National]].\n\nIn 1905, Jackson worked his way to [[Europe]] on a cattle boat, returning by the same means and travelling on to [[Chicago]]. In Chicago, he joined a commercial art firm and took courses at the [[Art Institute of Chicago]]. He saved his earnings and, by 1907, was able to visit [[France]] to study [[Impressionism]]. In France, Jackson decided to become a professional painter, studying at [[Paris]]' [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]]<ref name = NGC/> under [[Jean-Paul Laurens|J. P. Laurens]]. Some of his most important artistic development was at the [[Etaples art colony]], which he first visited in 1908 with his New Zealand friend [[Eric Spencer Macky]] (1880\u20131958). Jackson painted his ''Paysage Embrum\u00e9'' then and, rather to his surprise, it was accepted by the Paris Salon.<ref name=\"Larsen\">{{cite book|last1=Larsen|first1=Wayne|title=A.Y. Jackson: The Life of a Landscape Painter|date=2009|publisher=Dundurn|isbn=9781770704527|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y1XlXIh1HKcC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=20 November 2016|language=en}}</ref>{{rp|30}} Returning in 1912, he stayed with the Australian [[Arthur Baker-Clack]] (1877\u20131955). From this period date the Neo-Impressionist ''Sand dunes at Cucq''<ref>http://visipix.dynalias.com/newsgroups/newsgroups/view_pic.php?ng=fine_arts&start=40&keywords=dune&lang=&pic_size=standard&group=0&searchmethod=fulltext{{dead link|date=March 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and ''Autumn in Picardy'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museumsyndicate.com/item.php?item=22013 |title=View online |publisher=Museumsyndicate.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref> which was bought by the National Gallery of Canada the following year.\n\n== Professional career ==\n[[Image:Red Maple (A. Y. Jackson).jpg|thumb|left|''Red Maple'' (1914), by A. Y. Jackson]]\n\nWhen Jackson returned to Canada, he settled in Sweetsburg, [[Quebec]], where he began painting works such as the Neo-Impressionist \"The Edge of Maple Wood\". He held his first single artist exhibition at the Montreal Art Gallery with Randolph Hewton in 1913. Unable to make ends meet and discouraged by the Canadian art scene, he considered moving to the United States. However, he received a letter from [[J. E. H. MacDonald]] which changed his mind. MacDonald inquired about ''The Edge of Maple Wood'', which he had seen at a Toronto art show, informing Jackson that Toronto artist [[Lawren Harris]] wanted to purchase the painting if he still owned it.\n\nAfter the purchase, Jackson struck up a correspondence with the two Toronto artists, often debating on topics related to Canadian art. Jackson soon began visiting Toronto. Dr. [[James MacCallum]] convinced Jackson to relocate to Toronto by offering to buy enough of his paintings for one year to guarantee him a living income.<ref name=\"Klages\">{{cite book|last1=Klages|first1=Gregory|title=The Many Deaths of Tom Thomson: Separating Fact from Fiction|date=2016|publisher=Dundurn|isbn=9781459731974|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7tAkCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=20 November 2016|language=en}}</ref>{{rp|24}} He moved into the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]] which was financed by Lawren Harris, heir to the Massey-Harris farm machinery fortune, and Dr. James MacCallum. Harris, overseeing construction of the building, was too busy to concentrate on his own artistic endeavours and loaned his own studio space, over the Commerce Bank branch at the northwest corner of Yonge and Bloor streets, to the newly arrived Montrealer, A. Y. Jackson. The spot is now occupied by the 34-storey 2 Bloor West. Jackson was a welcome addition to the Toronto art scene, having traveled in Europe and bringing with him a respected&nbsp;\u2013 though as yet not particularly successful&nbsp;\u2013 talent. The canvas taking shape while he waited to move into the Studio Building, ''Terre Sauvage'', became one of his most famous. In January 1914 the Studio Building was ready for occupation. [[Tom Thomson]] was another of the first residents of the building and shared a studio with Jackson for a year.<ref name=Klages/>{{rp|24}}<ref name=\"en.wikipedia.org\">[[Studio Building (Toronto)]]</ref> Like the other Group of Seven painters, Jackson embraced landscape themes and sought to develop a bold style. An avid outdoorsman, Jackson became good friends with [[Tom Thomson]], and the duo often fished and sketched together, beginning with a trip to Algonquin Park in fall 1914.<ref name=Klages/>{{rp|25}} Inspired by Thomson, Jackson and the other painters who would one day be known as the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]] undertook trips to [[Algonquin Park]], [[Georgian Bay]], [[Algoma District, Ontario|Algoma]] and the [[North Shore (Lake Superior)|North Shore]].\n\nWith the outbreak of [[World War I]], Jackson enlisted in the [[Canadian Forces Land Force Command|Canadian Army]]'s 60th battalion in 1915. Soon after he reached the front he was wounded at the Battle of Sanctuary Wood in June 1916 and found himself once more at \u00c9taples in the hospital there.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WGjfZPizNQIC&pg=PT99&lpg=PT99&dq=Arthur+Baker+Clack+Etaples#v=onepage&q=%20%C3%89taples%20&f=false |title=Defiant Spirits: The Modernist Revolution of the Group of Seven - Ross King - Google Books |date= 2010-09-25|accessdate=2014-07-26|isbn=9781553658078 |last1=King |first1=Ross }}</ref> While recovering from his injuries, he came to the attention of [[Lord Beaverbrook]].<ref name=\"Brandon\">{{cite book|last1=Brandon|first1=Laura|title=Art and war|date=2007|publisher=I.B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=9781845112370}}</ref>{{rp|46}} He was then transferred to the [[Canadian War Records]] branch as an artist. Here, Jackson would create important pictures of events connected with the war.<ref name=\"Gallatin\">{{cite book|last1=Gallatin|first1=Albert Eugene|title=Art and the Great War|date=1919|publisher=E.P. Dutton & Company|page=141|url=https://archive.org/stream/artandgreatwar00gallgoog#page/n132/mode/2up|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref><ref>Gallatin, Albert. (1919). {{Google books|zeAMAAAAYAAJ|''Art and the Great War,'' p. 141.|page=141}}</ref> He later worked for the [[Canadian war memorials|Canadian War Memorials]] as an [[Canadian official war artists|official war artist]] from 1917 to 1919.\n\nOn his return from WWI, Jackson again took up residence at the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]]. He removed Tom Thomson's easel, made by Thomson's own hand, from his studio and used it for all the subsequent pictures he produced in the Studio Building. Shortly after he returned from wintering on Georgian Bay, he learned that in his absence he had been included in an informal group of Studio Building artists, exhibiting for the first time, called the Group of Seven.<ref name=\"en.wikipedia.org\"/>\n\nThe [[Beaver Hall Group]] was formed in Montreal in May 1920 with A. Y. Jackson as president. In his opening speech, Jackson emphasized the right of the artist to paint what they feel \"with utter disregard for what has hitherto been considered requisite to the acceptance of the work at the recognized art exhibitions in Canadian centres. \"Schools and 'isms' do not trouble us\", he maintained, \"individual expression is our chief concern\".<ref name=\"Meadowcraft\">{{cite book|last1=Meadowcroft|first1=Barbara|title=Painting friends : the Beaver Hall women painters|date=2000|publisher=V\u00e9hicule Press|location=[Montr\u00e9al]|isbn=9781550651256|edition=[Nachdr.]|oclc=45044300}}</ref> He identified its goals as being those of the Group of Seven, and over the years Jackson maintained the contact between Toronto and Montreal, supporting and stimulating the Montreal artists through regular visits and correspondence. He kept them informed of events in Toronto and arranged for their works to be included in the Group of Seven exhibitions.<ref name=\"NGC30s\">{{cite book|title=Canadian Paintings in the Thirties|date=1975|publisher=National Gallery of Canada|chapter-url=http://www.kidsfashionstyles.com/best-art-easels-kids/|accessdate=20 November 2016|chapter=The Beaver Hall Group|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510111118/http://cybermuse.gallery.ca/cybermuse/enthusiast/thirties/html_chapters/catalogue_2_en.html|archive-date=2017-05-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> It is through this association he made lifelong friends of Beaver Hall artists [[Anne Savage (artist)|Anne Savage]], [[Sarah Robertson]] and [[Kathleen Morris]].<ref name=Meadowcraft />\n\nIn 1938, Jackson visited the mine-site of the isolated [[Radium]] [[Mining|mine]] at [[Port Radium, Northwest Territories]], in 1938.<ref name=\"AsiaOne2012-11-14\">{{cite news|url=http://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest%2BNews/Plush/Story/A1Story20121114-383365.html|title=Painting tied to Manhattan Project to be auctioned|date=2012-11-14|accessdate=2012-12-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306162744/http://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest%2BNews/Plush/Story/A1Story20121114-383365.html|archivedate=2016-03-06|publisher=[[Asia One]]|quote=A 74-year-old painting depicting the Canadian mine that produced uranium for the world's first atomic bomb will go under the hammer in Toronto on November 22, set to fetch up to Can$300,000 (S$367,000).}}</ref> Jackson was a friend of prospector [[Gilbert LaBine]], then the mine manager, and flew to the site with him, where he painted ''[[Radium Mine]]''.<ref name=\"Yahoo2012-11-13\">{{cite news|url=http://ca.news.yahoo.com/blogs/dailybrew/long-unseen-radium-mine-painting-group-seven-great-221015415.html|title=Long unseen, 'Radium Mine' by Group of Seven great A.Y. Jackson has nuclear significance|author=Steve Murti|date=2012-11-13|accessdate=2012-12-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fca.news.yahoo.com%2Fblogs%2Fdailybrew%2Flong-unseen-radium-mine-painting-group-seven-great-221015415.html&date=2012-12-02|archivedate=2012-12-02|publisher=[[Yahoo News]]|quote=Jackson painted the work, along with one other now hanging in the National Gallery of Canada, during a 1938 visit to the Northwest Territories mine owned by his friend Gerald LaBine. The operation was on the eastern shore of Great Bear Lake, about 440 kilometres northwest of Yellowknife.}}</ref> \n\nJackson left the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]] in 1955 with [[Lawren Harris]] mourning, in a letter from Vancouver, \"Your moving from the Studio Building marks the end of an era, the one era of creative art that has the greatest significance for Canada... You were the real force and inspiration that led all of us into a modern conception that suited this country, and the last to leave the home base of operations.\"<ref name=\"en.wikipedia.org\"/>\n\n== Group of Seven ==\n[[File:Group-of-seven-artists.jpg|thumb|Group of seven artists: [[Frederick Varley]], A. Y. Jackson, [[Lawren Harris]], Fairley, [[Frank Johnston (artist)]], [[Arthur Lismer]], and [[J. E. H. MacDonald]]]]\n\nIn 1919, Jackson and six painter colleagues formed the Group of Seven. These artists were considered to be bold, because the Canadian wilderness had previously been considered too rugged and wild to be painted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomthomson.org/groupseven/about1.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-04-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060427070315/http://www.tomthomson.org/groupseven/about1.html |archivedate=2006-04-27 }}</ref>  Although his name is conventionally associated with this group, he would also remain something of a loner throughout his life.<ref name=\"Reid\">{{cite book|last1=Reid|first1=Dennis|title=A concise history of Canadian painting|date=1988|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Toronto|isbn=9780195406634|edition=2nd|url=https://archive.org/details/concisehistoryof00reid_0|url-access=registration}}</ref>{{rp|191}}\n\nIn 1925, he taught at the [[Ontario College of Art]] in Toronto; this was the only year that he missed his annual spring trip to Quebec.\n\nIn 1933, Jackson helped found the [[Canadian Group of Painters]]. Several members of the Group of Seven later became members of this group, including [[Lawren Harris]], [[A. J. Casson]], [[Arthur Lismer]] and [[Franklin Carmichael]].\n\nLike the other members of the [[Group of Seven]] many of his works began as tiny [[en plein air]] sketches in oil on hardboard.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n== Later years ==\nIn 1954 he was one of eighteen Canadian artists commissioned by the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] to paint a [[mural]] for the interior of one of the new [[Park series|Park cars]] entering service on the new ''[[Canadian (train)|Canadian]]'' transcontinental train. Each the murals depicted a different national or provincial park; Jackson's was [[Kokanee Glacier Provincial Park]].<ref name=\"cr2004\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.exporail.org/can_rail/Canadian%20Rail_no503_2004.pdf | title=The 50th Anniversary of the CPR Stainless Steel Passenger Fleet | journal=Canadian Rail | date=November{{ndash}}December 2004 | issue=503 | pages=211\u2013223}}</ref> Jackson moved to the Ottawa region in 1955, settling in [[Manotick]].\n\nIn his later years, he was often accompanied on his painting trips into the Ottawa Valley region, the Gatineau Hills, the Lievre River Valley and Ripond by friend, painter and former student [[Ralph Wallace Burton]], and fellow painters Maurice Haycock and Stuart D. Helmsley.<ref name=\"ottawariverinstitute.ca\">[http://www.ottawariverinstitute.ca/art-gallery/ay-jackson-trail/437-ralph-burton ]{{dead link|date=December 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.walkersauctions.com/cat0505/walk18to46.pdf ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314163542/http://www.walkersauctions.com/cat0505/walk18to46.pdf |date=March 14, 2012 }}</ref> One such venture almost ended in disaster: \"[I]n the 1950s, when Ralph and A.Y. were painting on the banks of the Ottawa River at Deux Rivieres, a bullet ricocheted off a rock where Jackson was sitting.\"<ref name=\"ottawariverinstitute.ca\"/>\n\nIn 1958, he published ''A Painter's Country'',<ref>{{ISBN|978-0-7720-1102-2}}</ref> an autobiography dedicated to the memory of Group of Seven member [[J. E. H. MacDonald]], who \"visualized a Canadian school of painting and devoted his life to the realization of it\".<ref>Jackson, A. Y., ''A Painter's Country'', [[Clarke, Irwin & Company]], 1958, Frontispiece</ref>\n\nIn 1964, Jackson submitted his own design during the [[Great Canadian Flag Debate|Great Flag Debate]]. It was similar in design to the [[Pearson Pennant]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.cbc.ca/arts_entertainment/visual_arts/clips/4627/ |title=CBC Digital Archives |publisher=Archives.cbc.ca |date= |accessdate=2014-07-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965, Jackson had a serious stroke that put an end to his painting career. He recuperated at the home of friend and painter Ralph Wallace Burton, and later moved to the McMichael Conservation Estate in [[Kleinburg]], Ontario.<ref name=\"ottawariverinstitute.ca\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ottawariverkeeper.ca/river/creative_flow_celebrating_four_ottawa_river_artists |title=Creative Flow: Celebrating Four Ottawa River Artists |publisher=ottawariverkeeper.ca |accessdate=2013-12-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214105103/http://ottawariverkeeper.ca/river/creative_flow_celebrating_four_ottawa_river_artists |archivedate=2013-12-14 }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.galeriemolinas.com/artist.php?id=125 |title=A. Y. Jackson |publisher=Galeriemolinas.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>\nJackson died in 1974, over the Easter holiday in a nursing home in Toronto. He is buried on the grounds of the [[McMichael Gallery]].<ref>Jackson, A.Y., 'A Painter's Country,' Clarke Irwin, 1976, Foreword by Naomi Jackson Groves</ref> His niece [[Naomi Jackson Groves]] published several books about his life and work including ''Two Jacksons'' (2000), an account of a shared trip through France and Germany in 1936.<ref name=\"CWAHI\">{{cite web|title=GROVES, Naomi Jackson|url=http://cwahi.concordia.ca/sources/artists/displayArtist.php?ID_artist=1295|website=cwahi.concordia.ca|publisher=Canadian Women Artists History Initiative : Artist Database : Artists : GROVES, Naomi Jackson|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"PenumbraTwoJs\">{{cite web|title=Two Jacksons Abroad|url=http://www.penumbrapress.com/book.php?id=181|website=www.penumbrapress.com|publisher=Penumbra Press: Books, Art Prints, Limited Editions, Collectibles|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* In 1967 Jackson was appointed a Companion of the [[Order of Canada]].<ref>[https://archive.is/20070930055607/http://www.gg.ca/honours/search-recherche/honours-desc.asp?lang=e&TypeID=orc&id=2056 ]</ref>\n* [[A. Y. Jackson Secondary School (Toronto)|A. Y. Jackson Secondary School]] in Toronto was named after Jackson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ayjackson.ca/ |title=A. Y. Jackson Secondary School, Toronto, ON |publisher=Ayjackson.ca |date= |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>  He attended the opening of the school in 1970.\n* [[A. Y. Jackson Secondary School (Ottawa)|A. Y. Jackson Secondary School]] in Ottawa is also named after him and opened in 1976.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ayj.ca/ |title=A.Y. Jackson Secondary School, Kanata (Ottawa), ON |publisher=Ayj.ca |accessdate=2013-12-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214093644/http://www.ayj.ca/ |archive-date=2013-12-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* In 1970, the [[Royal Canadian Academy]] awarded Jackson its medal for lifetime achievement.<ref>Jackson, A. Y., ''A Painter's Country'', Clarke Irwin, 1976, Foreword by Naomi Jackson Groves</ref>\n* The A. Y. Jackson Lookout on [[Ontario Highway 144|Highway 144]] in [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]] overlooks the waterfall depicted in Jackson's 1953 painting ''Spring on the Onaping River''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boldts.net/album/Onaping.shtml |title=Spring on the Onaping River |publisher=Boldts.net |date= |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>\n* The Ottawa River Institute has established an A. Y. Jackson Trail in his honour.<ref>[http://www.ottawariverinstitute.ca/art-gallery/ay-jackson-trail ]{{dead link|date=December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Paintings==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"230px\">\nFile:A. Y. Jackson - Cathedral at Ypres, Belgium.jpg|''Cathedral at Ypres, Belgium'', 1917, [[McMichael Canadian Art Collection]], [[Kleinburg]], Ontario\nFile:A. Y. Jackson -House of Ypres.jpg|''House of Ypres'', 1917\u201318, [[Canadian War Museum]], [[Ottawa]], Ontario\nFile:A. Y. Jackson - Gas Attack, Lievin.jpeg|''Gas Attack, Lievin'', 1918, Canadian War Museum, Ottawa, Ontario\nFile:A.Y. Jackson - Vimy Ridge from Souchez Valley.jpeg|''Vimy Ridge from Souchez Valley'', 1917, Canadian War Museum, Ottawa, Ontario\nFile:A.Y. Jackson - The Pimple, Evening (1918).jpeg|''The Pimple, Evening'', 1918, Canadian War Museum, Ottawa, Ontario\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Canadian official war artists]]\n* [[Military art|War art]]\n* [[Studio Building (Toronto)|The Studio Building]], Toronto, the home and working studio of several Group of Seven painters\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{citation |last =Boulet |first = Roger |author2=Group of Seven|author3=Tom Thomson |year =1982 |title = The Canadian Earth |url = http://collectionscanada.gc.ca/ourl/res.php?url_ver=Z39.88-2004&url_tim=2011-06-25T20%3A38%3A38Z&url_ctx_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=2894383&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fcollectionscanada.gc.ca%3Aamicus|publisher=[[M. Bernard Loates]], Cerebrus Publishing |isbn=0920016103 |accessdate = }}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|A. Y. Jackson}}\n* {{OCC|2056}}\n*[http://thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/ay-jackson The Canadian Encyclopedia, A.Y. Jackson]\n*[http://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/arts-entertainment/visual-arts/the-group-of-seven-painters-in-the-wilderness/ay-jackson-still-painting-at-73.html CBC Digital Archives - The Group of Seven: Painters in the Wilderness]\n*[http://www.nfb.ca/film/canadian_landscape/ ''Canadian Landscape'' - an online documentary at NFB.ca]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110929000723/http://www.pwnhc.ca/timeline/index_winIFix.asp?forward=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.pwnhc.ca%2Ftimeline%2F1925%2F1928JacksonBanting.htm 1928 A.Y. Jackson and Frederick Banting] NWT Historical Timeline, Prince of Wales Northern Heritage Centre\n* [http://digitallibrary.uleth.ca/cdm4/results.php?CISOOP1=exact&CISOFIELD1=CISOSEARCHALL&CISOROOT=/lc&CISOBOX1=Jackson%2C+A.+Y.+%28Alexander+Young%29%2C+1882-1974 A. Y. Jackson, Lethbridge College Buchanan Art Collection]\n* [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0772011028 A Painter's Country on Amazon.com]\n\n{{Tom Thomson}}\n{{Group of Seven|state=expanded}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jackson, A.Y.}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1974 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian male painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian Companions of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Canadian landscape painters]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Artists from Montreal]]\n[[Category:School of the Art Institute of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Acad\u00e9mie Julian]]\n[[Category:Anglophone Quebec people]]\n[[Category:Persons of National Historic Significance (Canada)]]\n[[Category:Canadian war artists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]]\n[[Category:World War I artists]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Geographical Society fellows]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name = A. Y. Jackson \n| image = Alexander Young Jackson.jpg\n| caption = Jackson at work in [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]] in Toronto.\n| birth_name = Alexander Young Jackson \n| birth_date = {{birth date|mf=yes|1882|10|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada\n| death_date = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1974|4|5|1882|10|3}}\n| death_place = [[Kleinburg]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| field = [[Painting]]\n| training = [[Monument-National]], [[Art Institute of Chicago]], [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] \n| movement = [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]]\n| works        =\n| patrons =\n| awards =\n}}\n\n'''Alexander Young Jackson''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CC|CMG}} (October 3, 1882 \u2013 April 5, 1974) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] painter and a founding member of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]]. Jackson made a significant contribution to the development of art in Canada, and was successful in bringing together the artists of [[Montreal]] and [[Toronto]].<ref name = NGC>{{cite web|author=A.Y. Jackson |url=http://www.gallery.ca/en/see/collections/artist.php?iartistid=2672 |title=A.Y. Jackson - National Gallery of Canada &#124; National Gallery of Canada |publisher=Gallery.ca |date= |accessdate=2014-07-26}}</ref> He exhibited with the Group of Seven from 1920. In addition to his work with the Group of Seven, his long career included serving as a war artist during World War I (1917\u201319) and teaching at the [[Banff School of Fine Arts]], from 1943 to 1949. In his later years he was [[artist-in-residence]] at the [[McMichael Gallery]] in [[Kleinburg, Ontario]].<ref name = NGC/><ref>[https://www.utoronto.ca/gallery/collection_pages/jackson.htm ] {{webarchive. |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051120043109/http://www.utoronto.ca/gallery/collection_pages/jackson.htm |date=November 20, 2005 }}</ref>\n\n== Early life and training ==\nAs a young boy, Jackson worked as an office boy for a [[lithograph]] company, after his father abandoned his family of six children. It was at this company that Jackson began his art training. In the evenings, he took classes at Montreal's [[Monument-National]].\n\nIn 1905, Jackson worked his way to [[Europe]] on a cattle boat, returning by the same means and travelling on to [[Chicago]]. In Chicago, he joined a commercial art firm and took courses at the [[Art Institute of Chicago]]. He saved his earnings and, by 1907, was able to visit [[France]] to study [[Impressionism]]. In France, Jackson decided to become a professional painter, studying at [[Paris]]' [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]]<ref name = NGC/> under [[Jean-Paul Laurens|J. P. Laurens]]. Some of his most important artistic development was at the [[Etaples art colony]], which he first visited in 1908 with his New Zealand friend [[Eric Spencer Macky]] (1880\u20131958). Jackson painted his ''Paysage Embrum\u00e9'' then and, rather to his surprise, it was accepted by the Paris Salon.<ref name=\"Larsen\">{{cite book|last1=Larsen|first1=Wayne|title=A.Y. Jackson: The Life of a Landscape Painter|date=2009|publisher=Dundurn|isbn=9781770704527|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y1XlXIh1HKcC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=20 November 2016|language=en}}</ref>{{rp|30}} Returning in 1912, he stayed with the Australian [[Arthur Baker-Clack]] (1877\u20131955). From this period date the Neo-Impressionist ''Sand dunes at Cucq''<ref>http://visipix.dynalias.com/newsgroups/newsgroups/view_pic.php?ng=fine_arts&start=40&keywords=dune&lang=&pic_size=standard&group=0&searchmethod=fulltext{{dead link|date=March 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and ''Autumn in Picardy'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museumsyndicate.com/item.php?item=22013 |title=View online |publisher=Museumsyndicate.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref> which was bought by the National Gallery of Canada the following year.\n\n== Professional career ==\n[[Image:Red Maple (A. Y. Jackson).jpg|thumb|left|''Red Maple'' (1914), by A. Y. Jackson]]\n\nWhen Jackson returned to Canada, he settled in Sweetsburg, [[Quebec]], where he began painting works such as the Neo-Impressionist \"The Edge of Maple Wood\". He held his first single artist exhibition at the Montreal Art Gallery with Randolph Hewton in 1913. Unable to make ends meet and discouraged by the Canadian art scene, he considered moving to the United States. However, he received a letter from [[J. E. H. MacDonald]] which changed his mind. MacDonald inquired about ''The Edge of Maple Wood'', which he had seen at a Toronto art show, informing Jackson that Toronto artist [[Lawren Harris]] wanted to purchase the painting if he still owned it.\n\nAfter the purchase, Jackson struck up a correspondence with the two Toronto artists, often debating on topics related to Canadian art. Jackson soon began visiting Toronto. Dr. [[James MacCallum]] convinced Jackson to relocate to Toronto by offering to buy enough of his paintings for one year to guarantee him a living income.<ref name=\"Klages\">{{cite book|last1=Klages|first1=Gregory|title=The Many Deaths of Tom Thomson: Separating Fact from Fiction|date=2016|publisher=Dundurn|isbn=9781459731974|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7tAkCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=20 November 2016|language=en}}</ref>{{rp|24}} He moved into the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]] which was financed by Lawren Harris, heir to the Massey-Harris farm machinery fortune, and Dr. James MacCallum. Harris, overseeing construction of the building, was too busy to concentrate on his own artistic endeavours and loaned his own studio space, over the Commerce Bank branch at the northwest corner of Yonge and Bloor streets, to the newly arrived Montrealer, A. Y. Jackson. The spot is now occupied by the 34-storey 2 Bloor West. Jackson was a welcome addition to the Toronto art scene, having traveled in Europe and bringing with him a respected&nbsp;\u2013 though as yet not particularly successful&nbsp;\u2013 talent. The canvas taking shape while he waited to move into the Studio Building, ''Terre Sauvage'', became one of his most famous. In January 1914 the Studio Building was ready for occupation. [[Tom Thomson]] was another of the first residents of the building and shared a studio with Jackson for a year.<ref name=Klages/>{{rp|24}}<ref name=\"en.wikipedia.org\">[[Studio Building (Toronto)]]</ref> Like the other Group of Seven painters, Jackson embraced landscape themes and sought to develop a bold style. An avid outdoorsman, Jackson became good friends with [[Tom Thomson]], and the duo often fished and sketched together, beginning with a trip to Algonquin Park in fall 1914.<ref name=Klages/>{{rp|25}} Inspired by Thomson, Jackson and the other painters who would one day be known as the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]] undertook trips to [[Algonquin Park]], [[Georgian Bay]], [[Algoma District, Ontario|Algoma]] and the [[North Shore (Lake Superior)|North Shore]].\n\nWith the outbreak of [[World War I]], Jackson enlisted in the [[Canadian Forces Land Force Command|Canadian Army]]'s 60th battalion in 1915. Soon after he reached the front he was wounded at the Battle of Sanctuary Wood in June 1916 and found himself once more at \u00c9taples in the hospital there.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WGjfZPizNQIC&pg=PT99&lpg=PT99&dq=Arthur+Baker+Clack+Etaples#v=onepage&q=%20%C3%89taples%20&f=false |title=Defiant Spirits: The Modernist Revolution of the Group of Seven - Ross King - Google Books |date= 2010-09-25|accessdate=2014-07-26|isbn=9781553658078 |last1=King |first1=Ross }}</ref> While recovering from his injuries, he came to the attention of [[Lord Beaverbrook]].<ref name=\"Brandon\">{{cite book|last1=Brandon|first1=Laura|title=Art and war|date=2007|publisher=I.B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=9781845112370}}</ref>{{rp|46}} He was then transferred to the [[Canadian War Records]] branch as an artist. Here, Jackson would create important pictures of events connected with the war.<ref name=\"Gallatin\">{{cite book|last1=Gallatin|first1=Albert Eugene|title=Art and the Great War|date=1919|publisher=E.P. Dutton & Company|page=141|url=https://archive.org/stream/artandgreatwar00gallgoog#page/n132/mode/2up|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref><ref>Gallatin, Albert. (1919). {{Google books|zeAMAAAAYAAJ|''Art and the Great War,'' p. 141.|page=141}}</ref> He later worked for the [[Canadian war memorials|Canadian War Memorials]] as an [[Canadian official war artists|official war artist]] from 1917 to 1919.\n\nOn his return from WWI, Jackson again took up residence at the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]]. He removed Tom Thomson's easel, made by Thomson's own hand, from his studio and used it for all the subsequent pictures he produced in the Studio Building. Shortly after he returned from wintering on Georgian Bay, he learned that in his absence he had been included in an informal group of Studio Building artists, exhibiting for the first time, called the Group of Seven.<ref name=\"en.wikipedia.org\"/>\n\nThe [[Beaver Hall Group]] was formed in Montreal in May 1920 with A. Y. Jackson as president. In his opening speech, Jackson emphasized the right of the artist to paint what they feel \"with utter disregard for what has hitherto been considered requisite to the acceptance of the work at the recognized art exhibitions in Canadian centres. \"Schools and 'isms' do not trouble us\", he maintained, \"individual expression is our chief concern\".<ref name=\"Meadowcraft\">{{cite book|last1=Meadowcroft|first1=Barbara|title=Painting friends : the Beaver Hall women painters|date=2000|publisher=V\u00e9hicule Press|location=[Montr\u00e9al]|isbn=9781550651256|edition=[Nachdr.]|oclc=45044300}}</ref> He identified its goals as being those of the Group of Seven, and over the years Jackson maintained the contact between Toronto and Montreal, supporting and stimulating the Montreal artists through regular visits and correspondence. He kept them informed of events in Toronto and arranged for their works to be included in the Group of Seven exhibitions.<ref name=\"NGC30s\">{{cite book|title=Canadian Paintings in the Thirties|date=1975|publisher=National Gallery of Canada|chapter-url=http://cybermuse.gallery.ca/cybermuse/enthusiast/thirties/html_chapters/catalogue_2_en.html|accessdate=20 November 2016|chapter=The Beaver Hall Group|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510111118/http://cybermuse.gallery.ca/cybermuse/enthusiast/thirties/html_chapters/catalogue_2_en.html|archive-date=2017-05-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> It is through this association he made lifelong friends of Beaver Hall artists [[Anne Savage (artist)|Anne Savage]], [[Sarah Robertson]] and [[Kathleen Morris]].<ref name=Meadowcraft />\n\nIn 1938, Jackson visited the mine-site of the isolated [[Radium]] [[Mining|mine]] at [[Port Radium, Northwest Territories]], in 1938.<ref name=\"AsiaOne2012-11-14\">{{cite news|url=http://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest%2BNews/Plush/Story/A1Story20121114-383365.html|title=Painting tied to Manhattan Project to be auctioned|date=2012-11-14|accessdate=2012-12-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306162744/http://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest%2BNews/Plush/Story/A1Story20121114-383365.html|archivedate=2016-03-06|publisher=[[Asia One]]|quote=A 74-year-old painting depicting the Canadian mine that produced uranium for the world's first atomic bomb will go under the hammer in Toronto on November 22, set to fetch up to Can$300,000 (S$367,000).}}</ref> Jackson was a friend of prospector [[Gilbert LaBine]], then the mine manager, and flew to the site with him, where he painted ''[[Radium Mine]]''.<ref name=\"Yahoo2012-11-13\">{{cite news|url=http://ca.news.yahoo.com/blogs/dailybrew/long-unseen-radium-mine-painting-group-seven-great-221015415.html|title=Long unseen, 'Radium Mine' by Group of Seven great A.Y. Jackson has nuclear significance|author=Steve Murti|date=2012-11-13|accessdate=2012-12-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fca.news.yahoo.com%2Fblogs%2Fdailybrew%2Flong-unseen-radium-mine-painting-group-seven-great-221015415.html&date=2012-12-02|archivedate=2012-12-02|publisher=[[Yahoo News]]|quote=Jackson painted the work, along with one other now hanging in the National Gallery of Canada, during a 1938 visit to the Northwest Territories mine owned by his friend Gerald LaBine. The operation was on the eastern shore of Great Bear Lake, about 440 kilometres northwest of Yellowknife.}}</ref> \n\nJackson left the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]] in 1955 with [[Lawren Harris]] mourning, in a letter from Vancouver, \"Your moving from the Studio Building marks the end of an era, the one era of creative art that has the greatest significance for Canada... You were the real force and inspiration that led all of us into a modern conception that suited this country, and the last to leave the home base of operations.\"<ref name=\"en.wikipedia.org\"/>\n\n== Group of Seven ==\n[[File:Group-of-seven-artists.jpg|thumb|Group of seven artists: [[Frederick Varley]], A. Y. Jackson, [[Lawren Harris]], Fairley, [[Frank Johnston (artist)]], [[Arthur Lismer]], and [[J. E. H. MacDonald]]]]\n\nIn 1919, Jackson and six painter colleagues formed the Group of Seven. These artists were considered to be bold, because the Canadian wilderness had previously been considered too rugged and wild to be painted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomthomson.org/groupseven/about1.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-04-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060427070315/http://www.tomthomson.org/groupseven/about1.html |archivedate=2006-04-27 }}</ref>  Although his name is conventionally associated with this group, he would also remain something of a loner throughout his life.<ref name=\"Reid\">{{cite book|last1=Reid|first1=Dennis|title=A concise history of Canadian painting|date=1988|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Toronto|isbn=9780195406634|edition=2nd|url=https://archive.org/details/concisehistoryof00reid_0|url-access=registration}}</ref>{{rp|191}}\n\nIn 1925, he taught at the [[Ontario College of Art]] in Toronto; this was the only year that he missed his annual spring trip to Quebec.\n\nIn 1933, Jackson helped found the [[Canadian Group of Painters]]. Several members of the Group of Seven later became members of this group, including [[Lawren Harris]], [[A. J. Casson]], [[Arthur Lismer]] and [[Franklin Carmichael]].\n\nLike the other members of the [[Group of Seven]] many of his works began as tiny [[en plein air]] sketches in oil on hardboard.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n== Later years ==\nIn 1954 he was one of eighteen Canadian artists commissioned by the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] to paint a [[mural]] for the interior of one of the new [[Park series|Park cars]] entering service on the new ''[[Canadian (train)|Canadian]]'' transcontinental train. Each the murals depicted a different national or provincial park; Jackson's was [[Kokanee Glacier Provincial Park]].<ref name=\"cr2004\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.exporail.org/can_rail/Canadian%20Rail_no503_2004.pdf | title=The 50th Anniversary of the CPR Stainless Steel Passenger Fleet | journal=Canadian Rail | date=November{{ndash}}December 2004 | issue=503 | pages=211\u2013223}}</ref> Jackson moved to the Ottawa region in 1955, settling in [[Manotick]].\n\nIn his later years, he was often accompanied on his painting trips into the Ottawa Valley region, the Gatineau Hills, the Lievre River Valley and Ripond by friend, painter and former student [[Ralph Wallace Burton]], and fellow painters Maurice Haycock and Stuart D. Helmsley.<ref name=\"ottawariverinstitute.ca\">[http://www.ottawariverinstitute.ca/art-gallery/ay-jackson-trail/437-ralph-burton ]{{dead link|date=December 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.walkersauctions.com/cat0505/walk18to46.pdf ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314163542/http://www.walkersauctions.com/cat0505/walk18to46.pdf |date=March 14, 2012 }}</ref> One such venture almost ended in disaster: \"[I]n the 1950s, when Ralph and A.Y. were painting on the banks of the Ottawa River at Deux Rivieres, a bullet ricocheted off a rock where Jackson was sitting.\"<ref name=\"ottawariverinstitute.ca\"/>\n\nIn 1958, he published ''A Painter's Country'',<ref>{{ISBN|978-0-7720-1102-2}}</ref> an autobiography dedicated to the memory of Group of Seven member [[J. E. H. MacDonald]], who \"visualized a Canadian school of painting and devoted his life to the realization of it\".<ref>Jackson, A. Y., ''A Painter's Country'', [[Clarke, Irwin & Company]], 1958, Frontispiece</ref>\n\nIn 1964, Jackson submitted his own design during the [[Great Canadian Flag Debate|Great Flag Debate]]. It was similar in design to the [[Pearson Pennant]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.cbc.ca/arts_entertainment/visual_arts/clips/4627/ |title=CBC Digital Archives |publisher=Archives.cbc.ca |date= |accessdate=2014-07-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965, Jackson had a serious stroke that put an end to his painting career. He recuperated at the home of friend and painter Ralph Wallace Burton, and later moved to the McMichael Conservation Estate in [[Kleinburg]], Ontario.<ref name=\"ottawariverinstitute.ca\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ottawariverkeeper.ca/river/creative_flow_celebrating_four_ottawa_river_artists |title=Creative Flow: Celebrating Four Ottawa River Artists |publisher=ottawariverkeeper.ca |accessdate=2013-12-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214105103/http://ottawariverkeeper.ca/river/creative_flow_celebrating_four_ottawa_river_artists |archivedate=2013-12-14 }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.galeriemolinas.com/artist.php?id=125 |title=A. Y. Jackson |publisher=Galeriemolinas.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>\nJackson died in 1974, over the Easter holiday in a nursing home in Toronto. He is buried on the grounds of the [[McMichael Gallery]].<ref>Jackson, A.Y., 'A Painter's Country,' Clarke Irwin, 1976, Foreword by Naomi Jackson Groves</ref> His niece [[Naomi Jackson Groves]] published several books about his life and work including ''Two Jacksons'' (2000), an account of a shared trip through France and Germany in 1936.<ref name=\"CWAHI\">{{cite web|title=GROVES, Naomi Jackson|url=http://cwahi.concordia.ca/sources/artists/displayArtist.php?ID_artist=1295|website=cwahi.concordia.ca|publisher=Canadian Women Artists History Initiative : Artist Database : Artists : GROVES, Naomi Jackson|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"PenumbraTwoJs\">{{cite web|title=Two Jacksons Abroad|url=http://www.penumbrapress.com/book.php?id=181|website=www.penumbrapress.com|publisher=Penumbra Press: Books, Art Prints, Limited Editions, Collectibles|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* In 1967 Jackson was appointed a Companion of the [[Order of Canada]].<ref>[https://archive.is/20070930055607/http://www.gg.ca/honours/search-recherche/honours-desc.asp?lang=e&TypeID=orc&id=2056 ]</ref>\n* [[A. Y. Jackson Secondary School (Toronto)|A. Y. Jackson Secondary School]] in Toronto was named after Jackson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ayjackson.ca/ |title=A. Y. Jackson Secondary School, Toronto, ON |publisher=Ayjackson.ca |date= |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>  He attended the opening of the school in 1970.\n* [[A. Y. Jackson Secondary School (Ottawa)|A. Y. Jackson Secondary School]] in Ottawa is also named after him and opened in 1976.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ayj.ca/ |title=A.Y. Jackson Secondary School, Kanata (Ottawa), ON |publisher=Ayj.ca |accessdate=2013-12-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214093644/http://www.ayj.ca/ |archive-date=2013-12-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* In 1970, the [[Royal Canadian Academy]] awarded Jackson its medal for lifetime achievement.<ref>Jackson, A. Y., ''A Painter's Country'', Clarke Irwin, 1976, Foreword by Naomi Jackson Groves</ref>\n* The A. Y. Jackson Lookout on [[Ontario Highway 144|Highway 144]] in [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]] overlooks the waterfall depicted in Jackson's 1953 painting ''Spring on the Onaping River''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boldts.net/album/Onaping.shtml |title=Spring on the Onaping River |publisher=Boldts.net |date= |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>\n* The Ottawa River Institute has established an A. Y. Jackson Trail in his honour.<ref>[http://www.ottawariverinstitute.ca/art-gallery/ay-jackson-trail ]{{dead link|date=December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Paintings==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"230px\">\nFile:A. Y. Jackson - Cathedral at Ypres, Belgium.jpg|''Cathedral at Ypres, Belgium'', 1917, [[McMichael Canadian Art Collection]], [[Kleinburg]], Ontario\nFile:A. Y. Jackson -House of Ypres.jpg|''House of Ypres'', 1917\u201318, [[Canadian War Museum]], [[Ottawa]], Ontario\nFile:A. Y. Jackson - Gas Attack, Lievin.jpeg|''Gas Attack, Lievin'', 1918, Canadian War Museum, Ottawa, Ontario\nFile:A.Y. Jackson - Vimy Ridge from Souchez Valley.jpeg|''Vimy Ridge from Souchez Valley'', 1917, Canadian War Museum, Ottawa, Ontario\nFile:A.Y. Jackson - The Pimple, Evening (1918).jpeg|''The Pimple, Evening'', 1918, Canadian War Museum, Ottawa, Ontario\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Canadian official war artists]]\n* [[Military art|War art]]\n* [[Studio Building (Toronto)|The Studio Building]], Toronto, the home and working studio of several Group of Seven painters\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{citation |last =Boulet |first = Roger |author2=Group of Seven|author3=Tom Thomson |year =1982 |title = The Canadian Earth |url = http://collectionscanada.gc.ca/ourl/res.php?url_ver=Z39.88-2004&url_tim=2011-06-25T20%3A38%3A38Z&url_ctx_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=2894383&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fcollectionscanada.gc.ca%3Aamicus|publisher=[[M. Bernard Loates]], Cerebrus Publishing |isbn=092