se Relations, 1600\u20132000: Volume I: The Political-Diplomatic Dimension, 1600\u20131930'' (2000) [https://www.amazon.com/History-Anglo-Japanese-Relations-1600-2000-Political-Diplomatic/dp/0333753879/  excerpt], first of five topical volumes also covering social, economic and military relations between Japan and Great Britain.\n* Morse, Hosea Ballou. ''The international relations of the Chinese empire Vol. 1'' (1910), coverage to 1859; [https://archive.org/details/internationalrel01mors online];  ''The international relations of the Chinese empire'' vol 2 1861\u20131893 (1918) [https://archive.org/details/internationalrel1917mors2 online];  ''The international relations of the Chinese empire'' vol 3 1894\u20131916. (1918) [https://archive.org/details/internationalrel1917mors3 online]\n* Nish, Ian. (1990) \"An Overview of Relations between China and Japan, 1895\u20131945.\" ''China Quarterly'' (1990) 124 (1990): 601-623. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/654639 online]\n* Nish, Ian. ''Japanese Foreign Policy, 1869\u20131942: Kasumigaseki to Miyakezaka'' (2001)\n* Nish, Ian Hill. ''The origins of the Russo-Japanese war'' (1985)\n\n===Others===\n* Bosworth, Richard. ''Italy: The Least of the Great Powers: Italian Foreign Policy Before the First World War'' (1979) \n* Hale, William. ''Turkish Foreign Policy, 1774\u20132000.'' (2000). 375 pp.\n* Lowe, C. J. and F. Marzari. ''Italian Foreign Policy, 1870\u20131940'' (2001)\n\n==Primary sources==\n* Bourne, Kenneth. ''The foreign policy of Victorian England, 1830\u20131902'' (Oxford UP, 1970.) pp. 195\u2013504 are 147 selected documents\n* Cooke,  W. Henry, and Edith P. Stickney, eds. ''Readings in European International Relations Since 1879'' (1931) 1060 pp\n* Gooch, G. P. ''Recent Revelations of European Diplomacy'' (1940); 475 pp detailed summaries of memoirs from all the major belligerents\n* Joll, James, ed. ''Britain and Europe 1793\u20131940'' (1967); 390 pp of documents\n* Jones, Edgar Rees, ed. ''Selected speeches on British foreign policy, 1738\u20131914'' (1914). [https://www.amazon.com/Selected-Speeches-British-Foreign-1738-1914-ebook/dp/B008400H7O/  online free]\n* Kertesz, G.A. ed ''Documents in the Political History of the European Continent 1815\u20131939'' (1968), pp. 1-385; 200 short documents\n* Lowe, C.J. ''The reluctant imperialists: vol 2: The Documents'' (1967), 140 documents 1878\u20131902. (American edition 1969 vol 1 and 2 bound together).\n* Lowe, C.J. and M.L. Dockrill, eds. ''The Mirage of Power: Volume 3: The Documents British Foreign Policy, 1902\u201322.'' (1972), 191 documents.\n* Temperley, Harold and L.M. Penson, eds. ''Foundations of British Foreign Policy: From Pitt (1792) to Salisbury (1902)'' (1938) [https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.2629 online], 608 pp of primary sources\n* Walker, Mack. ed. ''Metternich's Europe, 1813\u201348'' (1968) 352 pp of primary sources in English translation [https://books.google.com/books?id=ExmvCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA352&lpg=PA352&dq=%27%27Metternich%27s+Europe,+1813-48%27%27&source=bl&ots=dF0CkgU7mD&sig=Qje_eixgsiUT2gdX_23GzM7y3vc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwitob7F5rPcAhVkja0KHf3TCtYQ6AEITzAG#v=onepage&q=''Metternich's%20Europe%2C%201813-48''&f=false excerpt]\n\n{{Great power diplomacy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:International relations (1814-1919)}}\n[[Category:History of international relations|*1814]]\n[[Category:European political history]]\n[[Category:19th century in politics]]\n[[Category:20th century in politics]]\n[[Category:Historiography of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:325d:5d00:297e:6125:911c:b973", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_relations_of_the_Great_Powers_(1814%E2%80%931919)"}
{"title_page": "African-American veterans lynched after World War I", "text_new": "{{short description|African Americans who were lynched in the U.S.}}\n[[File:369th 15th New York.jpg|thumb|alt=B&W photo of Men in uniform|Soldiers of the [[369th Infantry Regiment (United States)|369th (15th N.Y.)]] who won the [[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de Guerre]] for gallantry in action, 1919]]\n[[File:Colonel Hayward's \"Hell Fighters\" in parade. The famous 369th Infantry of (African American) fighte . . . - NARA - 533518.jpg|thumb|alt=B&W image of men marching|Colonel Hayward's \"Hell Fighters\" in parade.]]\n[[File:Sunflower River Bridge, Clarksdale, Mississippi (1890).jpg|thumb|alt=B&W photo of a bridge|Black veteran L.B. Reed was suspected of having a relationship with a white woman and hanged over the Sunflower River Bridge, Clarksdale, Mississippi]]\n{{also|Red summer}}\nWhen they returned home from [[World War I]], African-American veterans faced heavy discrimination. This article focuses on those '''African American veterans who were lynched after World War I'''.\n\n==Background==\n===WWI===\nWorld War I ended with the signing of the [[Armistice of 11 November 1918|Armistice of November 11, 1918]]. Though the fighting stopped, the war's potential to resume still existed and peace was only reached when representatives of Germany signed the [[Treaty of Versailles]] on June 28, 1919, exactly five years after the [[assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand]]. The United States entered the war after it had been raging for years. When it did send men to the fronts of Europe, the [[United States Armed Forces]] remained segregated, with all-black and all-white units. Despite the segregation, many African Americans still volunteered to join the [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] war effort. By the time of the armistice with Germany, more than 350,000 African Americans had joined the military to serve with the [[American Expeditionary Forces]] (AEF) on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]].<ref name=\"Gilmore p.\">{{Harvard citation no brackets|Gilmore|2007|p=}}</ref>\n\n===Reaction to returning Vets===\nDuring a homecoming celebration for African-American veterans of World War I in [[Norfolk, Virginia]] a [[1919 Norfolk race riot|race riot]] broke out on July 21, 1919. At least two people were killed and six people were shot. City officials had to call in the Marines and Navy personnel to restore order.\n\nOn August 16, 1917, [[James K. Vardaman|Senator James K. Vardaman]] of Mississippi spoke of his fear of Black veterans returning to the South, as he viewed that it would \u201cinevitably lead to disaster.\"{{sfn|Equal Justice Initiative|2019|p=}} To the American South, the use of black soldiers in the military was a threat, not a virtue. \u201cImpress the negro with the fact that he is defending the flag, inflate his untutored soul with military airs, teach him that it is his duty to keep the emblem of the Nation flying triumphantly in the air,\u201d and, the senator cautioned, \u201cit is but a short step to the conclusion that his political rights must be respected.\"{{sfn|Equal Justice Initiative|2019|p=}}\n\nOften violence broke out between serving members of the military. In both the [[Bisbee Riot|Bisbee Race Riot (July 3, 1919)]] and the [[New London riots of 1919]] active African-American service members were attacked by white mobs or white military units.\n\nMany Black soldiers in the years after the war were threatened with violence if they were caught wearing their uniform.{{sfn|Equal Justice Initiative|2019|p=}} Many others were even physically attacked, sometimes barely escaping with their lives. During an April 5, 1919, market day in [[Sylvester, Georgia]], Black veteran [[Daniel Mack]] was walking through a busy street and brushed against a white man. The white man was offended that Mack didn't show the proper amount of respect and the two got in a scuffle; police came on the scene and promptly arrested Mack for assault. He was sentenced to 30 days in prison. A few days into his sentence, on April 14, a white mob broke into the prison, took him out into the wilderness and lynched Mack; he survived by playing dead.{{sfn|James|2013|p=79}} No arrests were ever made.{{sfn|The Chicago Defender|1919|p=}} [[Newberry 1919 lynching attempt|Elisha Harper]], 25 years old, was the son of the Rev. T. F. Harper, a respectable and \"well-behaved preacher\" living in Helena.{{sfn|The Bamberg Herald|1919|p=1}} He fought in the army during [[World War I]] and just returned from Europe. On July 24, 1919, while walking the streets of [[Newberry, South Carolina]], he allegedly insulted a 14-year-old girl, who promptly reported him to the authorities. Harper was arrested and thrown in jail. Soon a white mob had gathered and would have lynched Harper if it was not for the local Sheriff who hid him away.{{sfn|The Herald and News|1919|p=1}}\n\n==Lynched African-American veterans ==\nThe following is an incomplete list of African Americans who had served in the military during WWI and were killed by white mobs with no trials for alleged crimes.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n|-\n! Name\n! City\n! County or Parish\n! State\n! Date\n! Accusation\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Lynching\n! style=\"width:3%;\" class=\"unsortable\"| Ref\n|-\n| Unknown\n| [[Pine Bluff, Arkansas|Pine Bluff]]\n| [[Jefferson County, Arkansas|Jefferson]]\n| [[Arkansas]]\n|\n| Insult of white woman - Refused to move off a sidewalk for a white woman\n| Tied to a tree with tire chains, and shot as many as 50 times\n| {{sfn|Equal Justice Initiative|2019|p=}}\n|-\n| {{Sort|Lewis, Charles|Private Charles Lewis}}\n| Tyler Station\n|\n| Kentucky\n| {{Sort|1918-12-16|December 16, 1918}}\n| Alleged robbery\n| Masked men stormed the jail, smashed the locks with a sledgehammer, and hanged him from a tree\n| {{sfn|Equal Justice Initiative|2019|p=}} {{sfn|Williams|2010|pp=223-234}}\n|-\n| Black Vet and a black woman\n| [[Pickens, Mississippi|Pickens]]\n| [[Holmes County, Mississippi|Holmes County]]\n| Mississippi\n| {{Sort|1919-05-05|May 5, 1919}}\n| Insult of white woman - Black woman wrote an \u201cimproper note\u201d to a young white woman\n|\n| {{sfn|Equal Justice Initiative|2019|p=}}\n|-\n| {{Sort|Truett, Robert |Robert Truett}}\n| [[Louise, Mississippi|Louise]]\n| [[Humphreys County, Mississippi|Humphreys County]]\n| Mississippi\n| {{Sort|1919-07-15|July 15, 1919}}\n| Insult of white woman - Alleged indecent proposal to a white woman\n| Hanged Robert Truett, a veteran who was 18 years old\n| {{sfn|Equal Justice Initiative|2019|p=}} {{sfn|Clark|2016|p=}}\n|-\n| {{Sort|Briggs, Clinton |Clinton Briggs}}\n| [[Lincoln, Arkansas|Lincoln]]\n| [[Washington County, Arkansas|Washington]]\n| Arkansas\n| {{Sort|1919-08-03|August 3, 1919}}\n| Insult of white woman - moved too slowly out of white woman's way\n| Chained to a tree, shot till dead\n| {{sfn|Equal Justice Initiative|2019|p=}} {{sfn|Encyclopedia of Arkansas|2019|p=}}\n|-\n| {{Sort|Reed, L.B. |L.B. Reed}}\n| [[Clarksdale, Mississippi|Clarksdale]]\n| [[Coahoma County, Mississippi|Coahoma]]\n| Mississippi\n| {{Sort|1919-09-10|September 10, 1919}}\n| Suspected of having a relationship with a white woman\n| Hanged from the bridge across the Sunflower River\n| {{sfn|Equal Justice Initiative|2019|p=}} {{sfn|Whitaker|2009|p=54}}\n|-\n| {{Sort|Crosky, Robert |[[1919 Lynching in Montgomery, Alabama|Robert Crosky]]}}\n| [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]]\n| [[Montgomery County, Alabama|Montgomery]]\n| Alabama\n| {{Sort|1919-09-29|September 29, 1919}}\n| Alleged assault of a white woman\n| Shot by a mob\n| {{sfn|The Gadsden Daily Times-News|2019|p=1}}\n|-\n| {{Sort|Phifer, Miles |[[1919 Lynching in Montgomery, Alabama|Miles Phifer]]}}\n| [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]]\n| [[Montgomery County, Alabama|Montgomery]]\n| Alabama\n| {{Sort|1919-09-29|September 29, 1919}}\n| Alleged assault of a white woman\n| Shot by a mob\