ve|2019|p=}} {{sfn|Whitaker|2009|p=54}}\n|-\n| {{Sort|Crosky, Robert |[[1919 Lynching in Montgomery, Alabama|Robert Crosky]]}}\n| [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]]\n| [[Montgomery County, Alabama|Montgomery]]\n| Alabama\n| {{Sort|1919-09-29|September 29, 1919}}\n| Alleged assault of a white woman\n| Shot by a mob\n| {{sfn|The Gadsden Daily Times-News|2019|p=1}}\n|-\n| {{Sort|Phifer, Miles |[[1919 Lynching in Montgomery, Alabama|Miles Phifer]]}}\n| [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]]\n| [[Montgomery County, Alabama|Montgomery]]\n| Alabama\n| {{Sort|1919-09-29|September 29, 1919}}\n| Alleged assault of a white woman\n| Shot by a mob\n| {{sfn|The Gadsden Daily Times-News|2019|p=1}}\n|-\n| {{Sort|Livingston, Frank |Frank Livingston}}\n| [[El Dorado, Arkansas|El Dorado]]\n| [[Union County, Arkansas|Union]]\n| Arkansas\n| {{Sort|1919-05-21|May 21, 1919}}\n| Alleged Murder\n| 100 people gathered to burn Mr. Livingston alive\n| {{sfn|Equal Justice Initiative|2019|p=}} {{sfn|Encyclopedia of Arkansas|2019a|p=}}\n|-\n| {{Sort|Johnson, Bud |Bud Johnson}}\n| [[Pace, Florida|Pace]]\n| [[Santa Rosa County, Florida|Santa Rosa County]]\n| Florida\n| {{Sort|1919-03-12|March 12, 1919}}\n| Alleged assault of a white woman\n| Chained to a stake, burnt alive His skull was split with a hatchet and pieces given to onlookers as souvenirs\n| {{sfn|Equal Justice Initiative|2019|p=}} {{sfn|Stevenson |2017|p=}}\n|-\n| {{Sort|McCarty, Lucius |Lucius McCarty}}\n| [[Bogalusa, Louisiana|Bogalusa]]\n| [[Washington Parish, Louisiana|Washington Parish]]\n| Louisiana\n| {{Sort|1919-08-31|August 31, 1919}}\n| Alleged attempted assault of a white woman\n| Mob dragged his body behind a car killing him before burning his corpse in a bonfire\n| {{sfn|Equal Justice Initiative|2019|p=}} {{sfn|Whitaker|2009|p=54}}\n|-\n| {{Sort|Green, Powell |Powell Green}}\n|\n| [[Raleigh County, West Virginia|Raleigh County]]\n| West Virginia\n| {{Sort|1919-12-27|December 27, 1919}}\n| Allegedly shot R.M. Brown, the white owner of a movie theater in Franklinton\n| Rope tied around neck, dragged for {{Convert|2|mi|km}} behind an automobile, then hanged from a pine sapling\n| {{sfn|Equal Justice Initiative|2019|p=}} {{sfn|The News Scimitar|1919|p=1}}\n|}\n\n==Aftermath==\n{{Main|Red Summer}}\nThese lynchings were among several incidents of civil unrest that are now known as the [[Red Summer|American Red Summer of 1919]]. Attacks on black communities and white oppression spread to more than three dozen cities and counties. In most cases, white mobs attacked African American neighborhoods. In some cases, black community groups resisted the attacks, especially in [[Chicago]] and [[Washington, D.C.]] Most deaths occurred in rural areas during events like the [[Elaine race riot]] in [[Arkansas]], where an estimated 100 to 240 blacks and 5 whites were killed. Other major events of Red Summer were the [[Chicago race riot of 1919|Chicago race riot]] and [[Washington race riot of 1919|Washington D.C. Race Riot]], which caused 38 and 39 deaths, respectively. Both riots had many more non-fatal injuries and extensive property damage reaching up into the millions of dollars.{{sfn|The New York Times|1919|p=}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[[Washington race riot of 1919]]\n*[[Mass racial violence in the United States]]\n*[[List of incidents of civil unrest in the United States]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|20em}}\n'''References'''\n{{refbegin|2}}\n*{{cite news |ref=harv|date= July 31, 1919|title= Newberry Negro Sought by Crowd|last=The Bamberg Herald|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn86063790/1919-07-31/ed-1/seq-1/#|newspaper=The Bamberg Herald|publisher=Henry S. Hartzog|location=[[Bamberg, South Carolina]]|issn=2379-4984|oclc=13608693 |pages=1-8|accessdate= July 21, 2019 }}\n*{{cite news |ref=harv|date= May 10, 1919|title= Soldier in Uniform is Beaten in Georgia Town|last=The Chicago Defender|authorlink=The Chicago Defender| newspaper=[[The Chicago Defender]]| loc